column17: First staging after primary with mets - skeletal and nodal metastases      Comment:    1. The left enlarged axillary lymph node is moderately FDG avid and is  suspicious for a lymph node metastases. This would be suitable for ultrasound  guided biopsy.    2. There are numerous FDG avid osseous lesions with no definite structural  lesion on CT. These are suspicious for widespread osseous metastases.  3. The lesion in the right temporal lobe is photopenic.    4. There is no abnormal uptake corresponding with the left submandibular space  mass. This appears separate to the submandibular gland and is indeterminate.  Although there is no FDG uptake surrounding this a necrotic lymph node is not  excluded. Further evaluation with post contrast CT neck is suggested.    5. Moderate FDG uptake at the porta hepatis does not appear to correspond with a  lesion on CT and is of unknown significance. This may represent low volume  metastatic disease.    6. There is no definite FDG uptake within the hepatic lesion. However, hepatic  metastases are not excluded.    7. Focus of moderate uptake in the spleen is not specific and can be kept under  review
column29: 1. Overall there has been progression of disease.    2. The left submandibular lymph node, although smaller in size, is newly  intensely FDG-avid, in keeping with progression. The left axillary lymph node  has increased in size and FDG activity.    3. Bone metastases have demonstrated a mixed response, some of the previous  lesions are more intense whilst others are less intense.    4. A new left upper lobe pulmonary nodule is FDG-avid in keeping with a  metastasis.  5. There are new FDG-avid hepatic metastases.  6. A right thyroid nodule is now FDG-avid, possibly a metastasis.  7. New FDG-avid peritoneal deposit in the anterior pelvis.    8. A new metastasis is seen within the tail of the pancreas, and possibly  near the pancreatic hea
column41: 1. Findings indicate a marked improvement post immunotherapy.    2. FDG avid 14 mm left axillary lymph node is in keeping with residual  metabolically active disease.    3. Elsewhere the previously demonstrated FDG avid metastatic disease has had  a complete metabolic response to therapy.    4. FDG uptake involving the soft tissues anterior to the body of the right  and left symphysis pubis suggests osteitis pubis
column53: 1. There has been a partial metabolic response in a left axillary lymph  node, which shows reduced FDG activity in the setting of previous left axillary  surgery. No FDG-avid lymphadenopathy is seen elsewhere.    2. There is a persisting complete metabolic response in the liver and no  abnormal uptake is seen in the region of the pancreas.    3. No FDG-avid pulmonary lesion is seen, with stable scarring at both lung  bases, particularly on the right.    4. Appearances suggest a complete metabolic response in previously FDG-avid  osseous lesions in the pelvis and spine.    5. There is however progressive increased FDG activity in the pubic region  and soft tissue anterior to the symphysis has increased, with new erosion at the  margins of the symphysis pubis. Infection is theoretically possible as a cause  for these appearances in the setting of a good response to therapy elsewhere,  however tumour is suspected. Clinical correlation is recommended with biopsy if  required.  6. No FDG-avid metastatic disease is identified elsewher
column65: An inflammatory appearing process is confirmed within the pubic  symphysis with an associated effusion, bony erosions, parasymphyseal bone marrow  oedema and associated soft tissue changes.    Review of the CT/PET studies indicates that this process has developed within  the last 4-5 months.  Infection must be suspecte
column77: 1. Status post left axillary dissection with a large post operative seroma  and low grade activity overlying this which likely represents inflammatory  changes in the skin and subcutaneous tissues. No focal intense uptake is seen.      2. Stable appearance in the lungs, with atelectasis in the lower lobes  bilaterally showing low grade FDG activity.    3. New uptake in the right sacral ala is in keeping with a recent  insufficiency fracture that was not evident on 12/02/2018.    4. There is also persistent intense uptake in the symphysis pubis which  appears slightly less active however, and the patient reports biopsy showing  inflammatory changes only. This presumably represents pubic symphysitis.  Infection cannot be excluded and there may be some instability resulting in the  sacral fracture on the right.  5. No distant FDG avid metastatic disease is identified elsewhere
column89: 1. A left axillary seroma has contracted since 09/05/2018 with moderate FDG  uptake at its margins which is likely inflammatory. No focal intense uptake in  the left axilla.    2. Low grade increased activity in small right axillary nodes that have  become more prominent is non-specific and may well be reactive. Ongoing  surveillance is recommended.    3. Stable appearances in the bony pelvis, with persistent uptake in relation  to the symphysis pubis that may well be inflammatory and there is a healing  right sacral ala fracture.    4. Atelectasis at the lung bases persists without evidence of pulmonary  metastatic disease.    5. Activity in the adrenal glands has increased slightly, particularly on  the left. column17: Staging PET    Post surgical changes are seen at the anterior aspect of the left shoulder. No definite evidence for residual disease is seen on this background. There is a discrete focus of activity superimposed over chest wall structures, lying anterior to the left 2nd rib, which is suspicious for a chest wall metastasis. There is intense activity at the lateral margin of a mass lying posterior to the spleen and very closely adjacent to the upper pole of the left kidney, felt in keeping with metastasis. A slightly lobulated low density mass lying medial to the left renal vessels is demonstrating subtle FDG activity, but also appears present and unchanged at a CT scan performed in October 2014. column29: Further progression - right supraclavicular node      Comment: In the interval since the October examination, the patient has developed an intensely FDG-avid right supraclavicular node. This is felt highly suspicious for metastatic disease. Further assessment at ultrasound and fine needle aspiration is recommended. There is also more prominent uptake at a lesion related to the isthmus of the right lobe of the thyroid. This could represent a second closely adjacent metastatic lymph node or possibly an incidental thyroid lesion. Ultrasound of this region is also recommended. There is more subtle uptake at a lymph node lying at the thoracic inlet to the right of midline which could be reactive to intercurrent pulmonary infection but must be viewed with suspicion in this setting and should also be kept under observation. There is persistent low to moderate grade activity at an asymmetric right level Ia lymph node which has not altered significantly in the interval. In October, further assessment of this node at ultrasound was suggested and it may have already been assessed. This may be a benign focus and its lack of alteration in the interval is noted, however, metastasis at this level is not excluded. No other definite evidence for metastasis is appreciated. High grade pulmonary uptake in a diffuse distribution including focal activity lying adjacent to the descending thoracic aorta within the apical segment of the left lower lobe is felt likely infective or inflammatory and some low grade uptake at mediastinal lymph nodes is felt reactive to this. There is some low grade activity associated with sites of dermal intervention at the left mandibular region. New activity in a preauricular region and associated with the external auditory meatus may be inflammatory and should be kept under observation

column125: Again note is made of cerebral, and to a greater extent cerebellar cortical  oedema. In addition, there is pathological leptomeningeal contrast enhancement,  which is most prominent over the left and right cerebral hemisphere. Given the  history, the appearances are presumed to be explained by melanoma metastatic  disease. Correlation with CSF findings is recommended. However, given the  symmetrical appearance, other aetiologies (inflammatory etc) cannot be excluded  on these imaging findings alone. Comparison with the previous examination is  difficult due to different MRI machines, and motion artefact. There has been no  convincing progression in disease when compared with the previous examination.  There may be slight improvement in the leptomeningeal pathological enhancement  over the left and right cerebral hemispheres. Cerebellar cortical oedema is  unchanged.

column29: Heterogeneously enhancing right axillary mass sandwiched between the right pectoralis major and minor musculature. column41: 1.	The current scan demonstrates several interval changes since the prior study which are difficult to unify on metabolic grounds.  2.	Extensive new avid right axillary nodes are highly suspicious of metastatic progression, with disease extending to the axillary apex / subpectoral region and right lateral chest wall.  Elliptical hypodensity in the surgical bed is likely attributable to a residual post-surgical collection.  3.	Interval increase in volume of avid bilateral pulmonary nodules with generalised parenchymal nodularity; these are indeterminate and difficult to differentiate between malignant (melanoma vs. thyroid) and benign (immune-related) aetiologies. Mild heterogeneous bilateral pleural uptake (R>L) is favoured to be inflammatory in nature.  4.	Symmetrical mediastinal/hilar nodes and upper abdominal nodal cluster raises the possibility of a granulomatous process, with nodal metastases a possible differential. Diffuse splenic uptake is likely reactive.  5.	Diffuse marrow uptake is likely reactive; the foci of relative prominence are less specific, and the possibility of osseous metastasis cannot be excluded.  6.	CT chest suggested to further characterise the lung changes, and early FDG-PET/CT follow up could potentially help to clarify current findings
